            ]
        },

        
        {
            "type": "heading",
            "comment": "Heading block",
            "text": "② Target Acquisition"
        },

        {
            "type": "columns",
            "comment": "Two-column layout test",

            "weights": [3, 1],

            "columns": [
                [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "comment": "Overview paragraph",
                        "text": "Use the sights to line up the target. The Panzerfaust 30 has a maximum engagement range of 30 meters, and as such only has one zero setting. Conversely, the Panzerfaust 60 is able to engage up to 80 meters, by using the ladder sight, you can switch between differing zeros. It's recommended that you aim center mass, as the innate inaccuracies of the round, and its high-arc may make precise firing difficult. Large targets such as the engine block are viable within 30 meters, however, any further than that one may struggle. Further, engaging moving targets at a distance will be difficult, as the round suffers from a very slow velocity."
                    }
                ],

                [
                    {
                        "type": "image",
                        "src": "panzerfaust30_j.png",
                        "caption": "",
                        "width": "50%"
                    }
                ]
            ]
        },

        {
            "type": "heading",
            "comment": "Heading block",
            "text": "③ Firing"
        },

        {
            "type": "text",
            "comment": "Overview paragraph",
            "text": "When engaging armored targets, such as the M4 Sherman, recommended engagement ranges are within 30 meters. From outside that distance, both Panzerfausts struggle to penetrate for immediate kills, however, large damage may still be inflicted upon the target and its occupants. When in doubt, wait for the closest possible engagement range.\nOnce firing is complete, dispose of the weapon, as spent tubes are useless and unable to be reloaded."
        }



